				<p>
					The concept of drafting – where moving objects are grouped tightly together to conserve energy by exploiting the lead object’s slipstream – has been around for years. From motorcycle racing to auto racing, cycling, speedskating, and more, sports enthusiasts and engineers are quite familiar with this aerodynamic technique for reducing drag and conserving energy while maintaining speed. 
				</p>

				<blockquote class="blockquote text-center pw-blue">
					<p class="mb-0">&ldquo;The connectors were fantastic . . .  I don’t think I would have had as fine a control as I had if I hadn’t been able to use the connectors in Pointwise.&rdquo;</p>
					<footer class="blockquote-footer"><cite title="Source Title">Michael Siemon</cite></footer>
				</blockquote>

				<p>
					This method would seem to make sense for commercial vehicles such as semi-trucks, which average a measly six miles per gallon of diesel.<a href="#ref1" class="page-scroll"><sup>1</sup></a>  With fuel making up about 38 percent of the cost of operating a truck fleet,<a href="#ref2" class="page-scroll"><sup>2</sup></a> any increase in fuel efficiency stands to significantly reduce costs. There is one problem, though: it is an extremely dangerous practice on the open road. To gain any real fuel efficiency, drivers would have to follow each other so closely they would not be able to brake or respond quickly enough in an emergency.
				</p>

				<p>
					Recent advances in automated vehicle technology are on the verge of changing that. Commonly referred to as platooning, this emerging technology can link heavy vehicles together using wireless communications, adaptive cruise control, crash avoidance systems, and automatic coupling /decoupling features that respond when other vehicles cut between two trucks. By being able to react to dangerous situations more quickly than a human driver can, platooning technology reduces the safe following distances enough for the drafting efficiencies to kick-in.
				</p>

				<h2>Environmental Benefits</h2>

				<p>
					In addition to increased fuel efficiency and safety, platooning technology has the potential for reducing the trucking industry’s carbon footprint. The Department of Energy estimates that 65 percent of today’s long-haul truck miles could be platooned with an overall four percent reduction in fuel consumption.<a href="#ref3" class="page-scroll"><sup>3</sup></a> Apply those numbers to the more than 30 billion gallons of fuel consumed by commercial trucks annually,<a href="#ref4" class="page-scroll"><sup>4</sup></a> and there’s the potential to removing carbon emissions from 1.2 billion gallons of fuel from our environment every year. 
				</p>

				<h2>Using CFD to Quantify Benefits of Truck Platooning</h2>

				<p>
					Computational fluid dynamics (CFD) studies play an integral role in quantifying the drag reduction and fuel efficiency that can be achieved from various platooning scenarios. As a graduate student at Auburn University, Michael Siemon recently contributed his CFD skills to a major, ongoing research project for the U.S. Army’s Tank and Automotive Research, Development and Engineering Center (TARDEC). While investigating the potential safety and fuel benefits of platooning is the goal of this study, TARDEC’s larger, long-term objective is to develop fleets of fully autonomous trucks that can venture over extremely rough terrains in combination with armored manned vehicles.<a href="#ref5" class="page-scroll"><sup>5</sup></a> 
				</p>

				<p>
					During the initial phase of the project, researchers used homogenous /identical vehicle meshes with very few details as a starting point, or &ldquo;baseline,&rdquo; to run simulations. The next step for Siemon was to develop a series of heterogeneous meshes with which to run CFD simulations — for example, positioning a truck with an empty load behind one with a full load to generate more realistic, real-world results. He began with computer-aided design (CAD) models of the trucks to create the meshes, a rather complex and detailed process.
				</p>

				<p>
					&ldquo;CAD models are not necessarially indicative of a final mesh. They may provide a basic skeleton, but you have to do a lot of fixing and some artistry even,&rdquo; says Siemon. &ldquo;Plus, ground vehicles have a lot more complexity than, say, a missile or plane. Things like wheels within wheel wells can be really tricky because you have two different surfaces working off of each other with a very small volume.&rdquo;
				</p>

				<h2>Creating Complex Automotive Meshes with Pointwise</h2>

				<p>
					By using Pointwise to build the grids from the imported CAD models, Siemon was able to refine the meshes to handle the complexities of automotive cases and generate more accurate CFD solutions. One of the biggest challenges was dealing with random volumes that were skewed and not located near walls or other features. The Pointwise connectors feature helped Siemon tackle that problem by giving him precise control over local grid spacing and ensuring that sharp edges in the geometry were accurately captured in the analysis mesh. 
				</p>

				<p>
					&ldquo;The connectors were fantastic,&rdquo; says Siemon. &ldquo;It made it so much easier to import the CAD models and resolve the areas that weren’t CFD ready. I don’t think I would have had as fine a control as I had if I hadn’t been able to use the connectors in Pointwise.&rdquo; 
				</p>

				<p>
					Another advantage with Pointwise, according to Siemon, has been its ability to generate meshes that work with most solver codes. For this project, Siemon used Tenasi: an unstructured CFD solver developed at the Chattanooga campus of the University of Tennessee. 
				</p>

				<p>
					&ldquo;Tetrahedra are probably the biggest challenge. They can be really thin or smushed,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;The solver can’t track the gradients across them, so you can get numerically unstable solutions.&rdquo;
				</p>

				<img data-src="images/Fig1-Volume-Grid-800x474.png"
				alt="Slice of the volume grid around a single box trailer vehicle" class="img-fluid center-block" class="img-fluid"/>
				<figcaption>
